                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*r86YlqWtf_D7pOVK"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@kazuend?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">kazuend</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Unsplash</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this article I am suggesting a new way of utilizing LLMs with your data. The approach consists of two stages: (a) Turning your data into a graph and (b) training a neural network on this graph.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In the first two Sections, I will explain how to achieve the objective (a) by first adding all the nodes (Section 1) and then adding all the links (Section 2).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In Section 3, I will show you how to utilize the new open source library “<a href="https://pypi.org/project/graphcolorflow/" target="_self">graphcolorflow</a>” to achieve objective (b) using unsupervised learning.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5"><strong>1. Turning Records into Nodes and Adding them to a Graph</strong></h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Let’s see how you can achieve objective (a). The new approach suggests that this could be done by using one of the advanced LLMs. You can start using these models by first installing the free Python library <a href="https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/installation" target="_self">“transformers”</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">&gt;&gt;&gt;pip install transformers</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now you need to choose one among the many available choices of very powerful LLMs that the library “transformers” provides. In this article I’ll be using the model “<a href="https://huggingface.co/xlm-roberta-large" target="_self">XLM-Roberta-Large</a>”. (I’ll not be getting into the question of the relative strengths of various other available models.)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Let’s assume that your data exists in the form of a list of strings. You can simply export your data using CSV format. Alternatively, it can be a list of JSON objects. A specific format doesn’t matter as long as at least some of the content is in natural language. Roberta is strong enough to figure out which part is actually in natural language.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">By processing each line separately, as a result we obtain a numerical array for each record in your data (by calling XLM-Roberta-Large).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">These numerical arrays encode the meaning of natural language content included in the records. They are cutting edge and are indeed very impressive.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you are an experienced deep learning practitioner, you probably already know various ways to make use of these arrays which involves building and training neural networks designed for various tasks.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">My new approach suggests an alternative way by first using the LLM to turn the data into a graph, and then use the LLM’s vectors again as a starting point for training a Graph Neural Network.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To turn your data into a graph you first need to turn each record into a node in some graph format. There are many graph processing libraries. Here we’ll use one called <a href="https://pypi.org/project/classidgraph/" target="_self">classidgraph</a>, because it is required by the library <strong>graphcolorflow</strong> which we’ll use in Section 3.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>classidgraph</strong> is “a Python Library for Managing Directed Graph”. The current version of <strong>classidgraph</strong> is 0.0.3.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">For each of your records, simply create a node in <strong>classidgraph</strong>. To do that you will need to give a unique Id for each record. You will provide a vector obtained from XLM-Roberta-Large to the constructor of each node.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now we have all the <em>nodes,</em> but we still need to add the <em>links </em>between them so that this will really be a graph and not just a set of records ported to a graph format.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I’ll describe how to do that in the next Section.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*gMwleFkj-FO8qu_6"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@scottwebb?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Scott Webb</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Unsplash</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">2. <strong>Adding all the Links to the Graph</strong></h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">For each node in the graph, you need to add some links to other nodes. This is easily done by using the distance between their vectors to find the most similar nodes. Simply add links to some subset of the found similar nodes (or to all of them). That’s all. Now you have a graph that has both nodes <em>and </em>links.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Of course it depends on your data, but it’s very likely that this procedure will give you a set of links that will prove useful for training Graph Neural Networks which will be discussed in the next Section.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">3. <strong>Training a Graph Neural Network with GraphColorFlow algorithm</strong></h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now we finally have your data in the form of a graph. So how can we obtain the enhanced vectors which will reflect YOUR data?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">For this we can use a graph neural network technology. This is why we turned your data into a graph in the first place (as described in the previous Sections).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/0*arg93uVB3DZeQ96s"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@vdphotography?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">VD Photography</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Unsplash</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Having your data in the form of a graph, enriched with the natural language vectors from <strong>transformers</strong> opens up a lot of possibilities. Now you can use graph based algorithms, either your own or provided by various libraries.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Alternatively you can use <a href="https://pypi.org/project/graphcolorflow/" target="_self">graphcolorflow</a>, a free open source library which was specifically made to be ready “out-of-the-box”. It enables unsupervised learning on directed graphs without unnecessary friction.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Install ‘<strong>graphcolorflow</strong>’ by running</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>&gt;&gt;&gt; pip install graphcolorflow</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The library provides a novel Graph Neural Network algorithm, also called “<a href="https://medium.com/@margaliot/getting-started-with-graphcolorflow-gcf-5c5c5bd143c3" target="_self">GraphColorFlow</a>”. You can use it to get enhanced vectors relating to your data.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The input to <a href="https://medium.com/@margaliot/getting-started-with-graphcolorflow-gcf-5c5c5bd143c3" target="_self">GraphcolorFlow</a> is your data, first enriched with LLM vectors and the converted to a <strong>classidgraph</strong> format. The algoritm returns enhanced vectors for all you records, but this is not all.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As the result of running the algorithm, you now also have <strong>a fully trained network.</strong> It can be used to generate similar enhanced vectors for <strong>entirely new records,</strong> that were not present at the time of the training of the model.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This feature is very useful if you have a very large number of records — say in the millions. You can train the networks on a much smaller representative sample of your data like 50,000 or so, and then use the trained networks on all of your data.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">4. <strong>Conclusion</strong></h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In Section 1, I described how to obtain natural language vectors for all the records in your data by using a LLM from the “transformers” library and to put your data enriched by these vectors into a graph format.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In Section 2, it was shown how to add links to most similar nodes based on the similarity of these vectors.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">While these original vectors obtained by LLM were useful for finding the links, it may not be immediately clear how to make further use of them for your applications since these models are trained on general data taken from all over the digital world, and not specifically adjusted to your particular data set.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In Section 3, I explained how you can easily obtain enhanced vectors by running the simple and easy to use GraphColorFlow algorithm. As a result of doing so, not only do you get the vectors for the records you have provided, but you also get a trained set of Graph Neural Networks reflecting the specifics of your data.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">===========================</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A premium ebook describing the working of <strong>ColorGraphFlow</strong> is available <a href="https://graphcolorflow.com/" target="_self">here</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>